Geochemistry of Rb and Sr

Rubidium (Rb)

  • Large-ion lithophile element (LILE), substitutes for K in K-bearing minerals.
  • Incompatible in mantle melting â Enriched in continental crust.
  • Found in micas, K-feldspar, and clay minerals.

Strontium (Sr)

  • Alkaline earth element, behaves like Ca.
  • Compatible in plagioclase, carbonates, apatite.
  • Found in basaltic rocks, limestones, and feldspars.

Rb-Sr Occurrence in Rocks

  • Rb-rich rocks:
    • Granites, pegmatites (High Rb/Sr ratio).
    • Metamorphic rocks (Hydrothermal sericite).
  • Sr-rich rocks:
    • Basalts, gabbros (Plagioclase hosts Sr).
    • Carbonate rocks (Sr in calcite).

Rb-Sr Decay System

Decay Equation

\[ ^{87}Rb \rightarrow ^{87}Sr + \beta^{-} \quad (t_{1/2} = 48.8 \text{ Ga}) \]

Isochron Equation

\[ \left( \frac{^{87}Sr}{^{86}Sr} \right) = \left( \frac{^{87}Sr}{^{86}Sr} \right)_0 + \left( \frac{^{87}Rb}{^{86}Sr} \right) \times (e^{\lambda t} -1) \]

Where:
- \(\lambda\) = Decay constant (1.393Â±0.004 Ã 10â»Â¹Â¹ yrâ»Â¹) .
- \((^{87}Sr/^{86}Sr)_0\) = Initial Sr ratio.

When to Use Rb-Sr Dating?

Best for:

  • K-rich minerals (Muscovite, biotite, sericite, K-feldspar).
  • Igneous, metamorphic, and hydrothermal systems.
  • Dating crystallization, hydrothermal alteration, and deformation.

Limitations:

â  Sr mobility in fluids can reset ages.
â  Metamorphism may disturb isotopic systems.

Applications in Mineral Deposits

Case Study: Rb-Sr Dating in Gold Deposits

See: Yu et al., (2025)

  • 1. Geology of the Study Area
    • Location: Liba gold deposit, West Qinling Orogen, China.
    • Host Rocks: Metamorphosed Devonian sedimentary rocks (siltstone, sandstone, shale).
    • Structures:
      • D1: Early cleavage formation.
      • D2: Main deformation event (NW-trending folds, reverse faults, stretching lineation).
      • D3: Post-mineralisation minor deformation.
    • Intrusions: Porphyritic granite and diorite dykes (associated with mineralisation).
  • 2. Style of Mineralization & Tectonic Context
    • Mineralisation Type: Orogenic gold deposit.
    • Gold-hosting Minerals: Arsenopyrite, pyrite.
    • Alteration: Sericitisation, silicification, chloritisation.
    • Tectonic Setting:
      • Gold mineralization linked to Triassic orogeny and collision of the North and South China blocks.
      • Gold deposited during late-stage hydrothermal fluid circulation in shear zones.
  • 3. Methods Used for Age Dating & Sericite Classification
    • In-situ Rb-Sr dating using Laser Ablation Inductively Coupled Plasma Tandem Mass Spectrometry (LA-ICP-MS/MS).
    • Micro-XRF mapping and trace element analysis to classify sericite into: See figures 4,5 and 6 in Yu et al., (2025)
      • Type I (Hydrothermal Sericite): Large, euhedral, high B, low Ba/Sr/Sc/V.
      • Type II (Interfered Sericite): Intermediate trace elements, mixed origin.
      • Type III (Metamorphic Sericite): Small, euhedral, high Ba/Sr/Sc/V.
  • 4. Key Results: Major Events & Their Ages
    • Gold mineralisation event: 208.7 Â± 4.3 Ma (Hydrothermal sericite).
    • Regional metamorphism: 427 Â± 44 Ma (Pre-mineralization event).
    • Mixed/overprinted sericite: 187â485 Ma (Multiple hydrothermal/metamorphic phases).
    • Implications:
      • Gold mineralisation occurred during Triassic orogeny, postdating metamorphism.
      • Mineralisation influenced by collision-driven hydrothermal processes.
      • Rb-Sr dating distinguishes ore-forming fluids from pre-existing metamorphic fluids.

Source: Yu et al., (2025)

Implications for Exploration

  • Rb-Sr helps date mineralisation and deformation events.
  • Can differentiate primary vs.Â secondary hydrothermal events.
  • LA-ICP-MS/MS technique allows online removal of isobaric interference, which reduce the time required for sample prepration.

Summary & Key Takeaways

  • Rb and Sr behave differently in geochemistry, affecting their distribution in minerals.

  • Real-world applications: Dating gold mineralisation, deformation, and fluid-rock interactions.
